The recently described entity ‘Tako tsubo transient cardiomyopathy’ (TC) has gradually penetrated cardiologists' awareness, while coming to be recognized as allowing for an amazingly rich spectrum of varieties, as reviewed briefly by Hasdemir et al. 1 On a rapid review, we can summarize the clinical features of such syndrome: 

1. tako tsubo transient cardiomyopathy is most frequently seen in post-menopausal females, but not necessarily (some 10% occur in males and some 10% in pre-menopausal females);

2. typically, it presents with a sudden onset, at the time of a stressful event, but it may also occur without any recognizable happening, in the life of the patient;

3. it may present with subjective symptoms (more frequently dyspnoea, chest, or abdominal pain), but it may also occur without any symptoms or different symptoms at different times;

4. it may severely compromise cardiac function, or not at all;

5. some patient recover quickly and to normality (the majority), but some may be in shock, pulmonary oedema, or even die of it;

